The paper deals with two problems related to voting, which are often studied in the field of computational social choice (cs.GT). The first problem is related to optimization and involves finding the optimal weighted lobbying strategy, which can be seen as a combinatorial optimization problem and is related to the study of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The second problem is related to determining the winner in Dodgson elections, which is a problem in computational complexity theory and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses approximation algorithms, which are often studied in the field of theoretical computer science (cs.CC), and probability distributions, which are relevant to the study of algorithms and data structures as well as discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
